WEBVTT

00:00.047 --> 00:02.382
<i>(Announcer) Previously,
on "Better Call Saul."</i>

00:02.422 --> 00:04.190
This is both strike one, and strike two.

00:04.344 --> 00:06.945
Howard can't just stick
you in doc review

00:07.046 --> 00:08.313
because of something I did.

00:08.414 --> 00:09.648
I told you this would happen.

00:09.749 --> 00:10.549
I screwed up!

00:10.650 --> 00:12.017
That came from a bullet!

00:12.118 --> 00:14.253
That's it, we're getting you
and Kaylee out of this house.

00:14.354 --> 00:15.220
Wallet!

00:16.289 --> 00:16.955
Let go!

00:17.056 --> 00:17.723
Oofff!

00:17.824 --> 00:18.423
<i>(Grunting)</i>

00:18.524 --> 00:19.224
That all you got?

00:19.325 --> 00:20.058
<i>(Tires screeching)</i>

00:20.159 --> 00:21.793
What did I do that was so wrong?

00:21.894 --> 00:24.263
<i>(Chuck) You're like an alcoholic who
refuses to admit he's got a problem.</i>

00:24.364 --> 00:25.631
<i>(Yelling)</i> Come on down, Chuck!

00:25.732 --> 00:27.949
Roll around in the dirt with me!

00:28.030 --> 00:30.364
â™ª

00:33.406 --> 00:37.009
[Electricity humming]

00:39.000 --> 00:45.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:57.597 --> 01:01.333
[Clock ticking]

01:16.115 --> 01:20.052
[Bill Evans'<i> "Gloria's Step"</i> plays]

01:27.785 --> 01:30.420
- Wonderful.
- Are the leeks too overpowering?

01:30.445 --> 01:31.270
Not at all.

01:31.388 --> 01:33.656
That's as good as the
one we had in Florence.

01:33.690 --> 01:35.725
- All right, don't humor me.
- I'm not.

01:36.727 --> 01:38.260
How was rehearsal?

01:38.295 --> 01:39.962
Did what's-her-name behave herself?

01:39.997 --> 01:41.864
She takes the whole section for granted.

01:41.898 --> 01:43.699
I'm debating whether to say something.

01:43.734 --> 01:46.102
I think you should, absolutely.

01:46.136 --> 01:47.603
Don't keep it inside.

01:47.637 --> 01:49.605
Ready for the chiffonade?

01:49.639 --> 01:51.974
- Yeah. Thanks.
- [Knife scraping]

01:52.009 --> 01:54.977
And after all, if she's
compromising the work...

01:55.012 --> 01:56.712
Mm. Well, it's debatable.

01:56.747 --> 01:59.515
I mean, the Schubert is
coming along nicely.

01:59.549 --> 02:01.550
It's more about morale.

02:01.585 --> 02:03.786
Morale can affect quality.

02:03.820 --> 02:07.189
God knows the hoops that
Howard jumps through

02:07.224 --> 02:09.758
- just to keep the troops humming.
- Well, true.

02:13.997 --> 02:16.132
You deserve a medal for this.

02:16.166 --> 02:19.769
Please. It's no big deal.

02:21.671 --> 02:23.172
Your soy-ginger marinade?

02:23.206 --> 02:25.541
Well, I found a citrus
one that looked good,

02:25.575 --> 02:27.309
so I thought I would try that.

02:27.344 --> 02:29.912
Well, anyway, you are a trouper.

02:29.946 --> 02:32.014
I apologize in advance.

02:32.049 --> 02:36.052
Let's just say he's... something
of an acquired taste.

02:36.086 --> 02:37.720
Oh, how bad can he be?

02:37.754 --> 02:40.489
Well, just in case,
let's have a high sign.

02:40.524 --> 02:41.757
[Timer beeping]

02:41.792 --> 02:43.359
How about the old Carol Burnett thing?

02:43.393 --> 02:44.760
Oh, where she pulls her earlobe?

02:44.795 --> 02:46.195
Exactly.

02:46.229 --> 02:48.998
You do this, and I'll say
I have briefs to read,

02:49.032 --> 02:51.033
and we'll get rid of him.

02:51.068 --> 02:52.568
- All right. Whatever you want.
- [Timer beeps]

02:52.602 --> 02:54.570
You know why she did that...
Carol Burnett?

02:54.604 --> 02:56.105
It's a great story.

02:56.139 --> 02:57.773
It was a signal to her grandmother,

02:57.808 --> 03:00.242
- who had raised her, as...
- [Doorbell rings]

03:00.277 --> 03:01.510
Seriously?

03:01.545 --> 03:02.878
He's early.

03:02.913 --> 03:05.114
- You're a doll.
- Mm.

03:05.148 --> 03:06.415
[Timer beeping]

03:06.450 --> 03:07.783
[Music continues]

03:07.818 --> 03:10.219
Holy shit. Look at this place.

03:10.253 --> 03:12.621
Hey, Jimmy, thanks for coming.

03:12.656 --> 03:14.423
Bring it on in here.

03:14.458 --> 03:16.358
[Chuckles] Oh, yeah.

03:16.393 --> 03:19.028
Hey! Little taste of home for you.

03:19.062 --> 03:21.597
[Chuckles] Had to look all over
town to find a place that had it.

03:21.631 --> 03:23.599
[Laughs] Didn't have time to wrap it.

03:23.633 --> 03:25.968
Well, thanks.

03:26.002 --> 03:29.872
[Music continues]

03:29.906 --> 03:32.041
You're good.

03:32.075 --> 03:34.643
Yeah. [Sighs]

03:36.313 --> 03:37.813
I'm looking for a place.

03:38.035 --> 03:39.902
- REBECCA: Mm-hmm.
- Been staying at the Ramada.

03:39.936 --> 03:41.604
And thanks for the help, by the way.

03:41.638 --> 03:43.005
I've found a few that I like.

03:43.040 --> 03:45.775
This one place, the
Beachcomber, has a pool.

03:45.809 --> 03:47.176
And since the McGill clan

03:47.210 --> 03:49.145
is whiter than a pack of albino rats...

03:49.179 --> 03:49.746
[Chuckles]

03:49.771 --> 03:51.447
...I figure I better
start working on my tan.

03:51.481 --> 03:53.015
So, seriously considering <i>that</i> option.

03:53.050 --> 03:55.418
I strongly suggest sunscreen.

03:55.452 --> 03:57.620
We're up about 5,000 feet here.

03:57.654 --> 03:59.021
You'll fry.

03:59.056 --> 04:02.458
Excellent point. Sunscreen... check.

04:02.492 --> 04:04.827
[Sighs]

04:04.861 --> 04:09.031
So... a violinist?

04:09.066 --> 04:10.766
Mm.

04:10.801 --> 04:14.437
And according to Chuck, a
crazy talented one at that.

04:14.471 --> 04:16.005
- Mm.
- I mean, wow.

04:16.039 --> 04:18.440
Well, Chuck is very gracious.

04:18.475 --> 04:19.975
She's being modest.

04:20.010 --> 04:23.112
Rebecca is widely respected
amongst her peers.

04:23.146 --> 04:25.815
- Mm.
- Yo-Yo Ma came to our wedding.

04:25.849 --> 04:27.616
That's, um...

04:27.651 --> 04:29.952
Right on, man.

04:29.986 --> 04:31.454
[Chuckles]

04:31.488 --> 04:33.356
About the wedding, um,

04:33.390 --> 04:36.659
I've been meaning to apologize...
about that.

04:36.693 --> 04:39.462
I am truly sorry I wasn't...

04:39.496 --> 04:42.098
No worries, please.

04:44.334 --> 04:46.202
[Clears throat]

04:46.236 --> 04:48.838
So, tell us about your first
week at Hamlin, Hamlin, McGill.

04:48.872 --> 04:50.539
It was great.

04:50.574 --> 04:53.209
I mean, they got me workin
in the mailroom, which...

04:53.243 --> 04:54.677
you gotta start somewhere.

04:54.711 --> 04:55.978
[Chuckles]

04:56.012 --> 04:57.480
I learned how to use the Xerox machine,

04:57.514 --> 04:59.548
which is surprisingly complicated.

04:59.583 --> 05:02.518
I mean, press a button, a
piece of paper spits out...

05:02.552 --> 05:03.753
- not anymore.
- Mm.

05:03.787 --> 05:05.654
Thing's practically a computer.

05:05.689 --> 05:07.823
It's like goddamn space shuttle.

05:07.858 --> 05:09.892
It's got, like, double-sided printing,

05:09.926 --> 05:11.560
automatic stapling, you know?

05:11.595 --> 05:12.895
Mm.

05:12.929 --> 05:16.866
Met some nice folks... guys and gals.

05:16.900 --> 05:20.503
Well, gal... singular, actually.

05:20.537 --> 05:22.104
[Sighs]

05:22.139 --> 05:25.341
Learned everyone's name, and
I licked a ton of stamps.

05:25.375 --> 05:28.344
My tongue is like hamburger meat...
I mean, seriously.

05:28.378 --> 05:29.845
Unh, aah?

05:29.880 --> 05:31.080
Yeah?

05:31.114 --> 05:33.182
I got... Thing's raw as hell.

05:33.216 --> 05:36.118
Then I found out there's
a sponge for that.

05:36.153 --> 05:38.020
Oops! Rookie mistake.

05:38.054 --> 05:39.688
[Chuckles]

05:39.723 --> 05:41.724
Well, it sounds like you had
a very productive week.

05:41.758 --> 05:44.560
Yeah, it was really great.

05:47.130 --> 05:48.597
Hey, guys, um...

05:48.632 --> 05:51.901
um, I want to thank you
for having me over.

05:51.935 --> 05:55.771
This is, like, the best
meal I've had in a decade.

05:55.806 --> 05:57.306
[Chuckles]

05:57.340 --> 06:00.543
I mean, the fish is
perfection, and the, uh...

06:00.577 --> 06:02.077
Risotto.

06:02.112 --> 06:03.379
Risotto.

06:03.413 --> 06:05.080
[Smooches]

06:05.115 --> 06:06.882
Thank you. That's very kind.

06:06.917 --> 06:09.285
Well, you're a wonderful chef, you know?

06:09.319 --> 06:12.388
Aside from being super
talented with the...

06:12.422 --> 06:13.989
Yeah.

06:14.024 --> 06:16.492
You got a good one, Chuck...
I mean, lucky, lucky man.

06:16.526 --> 06:19.128
- [Chuckles]
- Well, cheers to that.

06:19.162 --> 06:20.463
Oh.

06:20.497 --> 06:22.798
[Soft music plays]

06:22.833 --> 06:24.900
[Clears throat]

06:24.935 --> 06:27.303
[Coughs] Pardon me.

06:27.337 --> 06:29.772
[Music continues]

06:40.350 --> 06:42.251
- All right.
- [Bottle thumps lightly]

06:42.285 --> 06:45.488
What's the difference
between a vacuum cleaner

06:45.522 --> 06:47.756
and a lawyer on a motorcycle?

06:47.791 --> 06:50.960
The vacuum cleaner has the
dirt bag on the inside.

06:50.994 --> 06:52.194
[Both laugh]

06:52.229 --> 06:53.796
[Chuckles] Aha, lawyer jokes.

06:53.830 --> 06:57.299
I've only been in the mailroom a week,
and I've heard maybe a hundred.

06:57.334 --> 06:58.968
- Yeah.
- It all comes from a place of affection.

06:59.002 --> 07:00.669
Sure. Of course.

07:00.704 --> 07:03.639
What do you get when you cross
the Godfather with a lawyer?

07:03.673 --> 07:05.608
An offer you can't understand.

07:05.642 --> 07:07.209
- [Laughs]
- Very clever.

07:07.244 --> 07:08.511
Never heard that one.

07:08.545 --> 07:10.212
And believe me...

07:10.247 --> 07:12.381
I have nothing but the utmost
respect for your profession.

07:12.415 --> 07:14.183
I mean, it's the pillar of... Oh!

07:14.217 --> 07:16.652
Why do they bury lawyers
under 20 feet of dirt?

07:16.686 --> 07:18.787
Because deep down, they're
really good people.

07:18.822 --> 07:20.389
[Laughs] [Chuckles]

07:20.423 --> 07:23.058
Uh, w-what do you call a
lawyer with an IQ of 60?

07:23.093 --> 07:24.660
- "Your Honor."
- [Chuckles]

07:24.694 --> 07:27.363
What's the difference between
a tick and a lawyer?

07:27.397 --> 07:28.797
REBECCA: Oh, no.

07:28.832 --> 07:30.499
The tick falls off
when you're dead! Bam!

07:30.534 --> 07:32.001
- [Laughs]
- Love that one.

07:32.035 --> 07:34.169
You like that? [Chuckles] Just joking.

07:34.204 --> 07:36.872
I want you to know how
seriously I take my job.

07:36.907 --> 07:38.140
That's great.

07:38.174 --> 07:39.842
I'm, uh, grateful for the... Oh.

07:39.876 --> 07:42.511
How many lawyers does it
take to change a light bulb?

07:42.546 --> 07:44.046
Classic setup here.

07:44.080 --> 07:47.750
Three... one to climb the
ladder, one to shake it,

07:47.784 --> 07:49.418
and one to sue the ladder company.

07:49.452 --> 07:50.686
[Both laugh]

07:50.720 --> 07:52.254
Comedy gold.

07:52.289 --> 07:54.757
- I'm here all night!
- More. Go, go. [Laughs]

07:54.791 --> 07:57.092
JIMMY: Okay. Okay, okay, okay.

07:57.127 --> 07:58.761
Dessert, anyone?

07:58.795 --> 08:01.530
We have a homemade blueberry
crumble with vanilla ice cream.

08:01.565 --> 08:03.566
Yeah, blueberry crumble...
sounds terrific.

08:03.600 --> 08:05.434
I love a fruit-based, uh, blueberry...

08:05.468 --> 08:07.870
- Wait. I think <i> I</i> know one.
- Oh, bring it on.

08:07.904 --> 08:09.405
Yeah, yeah.

08:09.439 --> 08:12.241
Um, what do lawyers and
sperm have in common?

08:12.275 --> 08:13.542
Oh, just... Um.

08:13.577 --> 08:15.177
3 million... No, wait.

08:15.211 --> 08:17.546
Um, 1 in 3 million...

08:17.581 --> 08:19.632
have a chance of becoming a human being.

08:19.657 --> 08:21.784
...a chance of becoming a human being.

08:21.818 --> 08:23.686
[Both laugh]

08:23.720 --> 08:25.788
Love that one.

08:25.822 --> 08:27.690
[Chuckles]

08:27.724 --> 08:29.358
[Laughs]

08:29.392 --> 08:32.361
[Crickets chirping]

08:32.395 --> 08:35.530
Well, that went well, don't you think?

08:35.565 --> 08:38.333
Sure. Thanks again.

08:40.135 --> 08:41.703
I don't know what you
were worried about.

08:41.738 --> 08:43.739
Jimmy's great.

08:43.773 --> 08:46.475
Yeah. No, he's...

08:46.509 --> 08:48.344
Yeah.

08:50.146 --> 08:51.947
So, what's going on tomorrow?

08:51.982 --> 08:53.482
[Inhales deeply]

08:53.516 --> 08:55.918
Well, I've got the Gernstetter
deposition at 10:00,

08:55.952 --> 08:58.320
back-to-back partner
meetings after lunch.

08:58.355 --> 09:00.756
It shouldn't be a late one.

09:00.790 --> 09:03.092
Thought any more about what's-her-name?

09:03.126 --> 09:05.260
It's your reputation, too, you know?

09:05.295 --> 09:06.595
[Sighs]

09:06.630 --> 09:08.397
Well, we start the
Tchaikovsky on Monday,

09:08.431 --> 09:11.333
so I'll see what kind of
mood she's in when we wrap.

09:11.368 --> 09:12.968
Smart.

09:15.972 --> 09:17.740
[Inhales deeply]

09:17.774 --> 09:20.743
What do you call 25 attorneys

09:20.777 --> 09:23.379
buried up to their chins in cement?

09:24.614 --> 09:27.349
Not enough cement. What?

09:27.384 --> 09:29.351
[Inhales sharply]

09:29.386 --> 09:31.420
Oh, oh, oh.

09:31.454 --> 09:33.589
[Chuckles]

09:33.623 --> 09:35.391
Yeah. Mm.

09:47.303 --> 09:51.707
